29
00:01:37,219 --> 00:01:41,810
My hope is that we can save as much as possible.


30
00:01:41,810 --> 00:01:46,399
I don't think there's any preventing
some of the effects of climate change.

31
00:01:46,399 --> 00:01:49,026
But let's save what we can.


32
00:01:50,027 --> 00:01:52,810
I really hope that we wake up.


33
00:01:52,810 --> 00:01:56,033
I hope we, I hope we
don't wait till it's too late.

34
00:01:57,321 --> 00:02:00,037
Today, I am well aware of what is going on.


35
00:02:00,484 --> 00:02:03,040
I can see it, it's right in front of me.


36
00:02:03,990 --> 00:02:05,459
I have two options:

37
00:02:05,729 --> 00:02:09,331
The first one is to see everything and sink


38
00:02:09,560 --> 00:02:11,618
and the second option,


39
00:02:11,618 --> 00:02:12,919
is to have energy


40
00:02:12,919 --> 00:02:14,526
and to be optimistic.


41
00:02:15,077 --> 00:02:18,126
My nature is not to choose the first option.


42
00:02:18,414 --> 00:02:23,018
You have to look for hope, and I think it's
less about you willingly looking, but kinda

43
00:02:23,018 --> 00:02:28,739
forcefully making yourself look at those
moments of hope, so that you don't get lost in the

44
00:02:28,739 --> 00:02:30,842
sort of depressing nature of it all.


45
00:02:32,069 --> 00:02:35,959
When it comes to hope,
it’s tempting to look for quick fixes.

46
00:02:35,959 --> 00:02:40,035
You know like renewable
energy or electric cars for instance.

47
00:02:40,035 --> 00:02:44,630
But if we really want to answer
the big question of “Is there hope?”

48
00:02:44,630 --> 00:02:46,730
we need to dig a little deeper.


49
00:02:46,730 --> 00:02:50,004
We need first to understand how we got here.


50
00:02:50,421 --> 00:02:55,530
Because the real puzzle is this, right: experts
have warned us for more than 50 years about

51
00:02:55,530 --> 00:02:59,770
all this stuff that we talked about right-
the relentless destruction of living systems

52
00:02:59,770 --> 00:03:02,016
and the pollution and the warming.


53
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:07,129
And heck, like 30 years ago, you know, political
leaders came together at the United Nations


54
00:03:07,129 --> 00:03:12,350
and signed a treaty to "combat dangerous
human interference with the climate systems".

55
00:03:12,350 --> 00:03:16,363
If only we had started
to act then, but instead of it,

56
00:03:16,363 --> 00:03:19,420
things have just gotten worse and worse.


57
00:03:19,420 --> 00:03:23,704
So we feel that we first need to
understand how come that we're so stuck,

58
00:03:23,704 --> 00:03:25,850
you know, digging our own hole.


59
00:03:25,850 --> 00:03:30,002
And only after that, we'll look
into the question of how can we change course.

60
00:03:31,420 --> 00:03:34,840
So I hope you're ready because
here we go with episode two.

61
00:03:35,420 --> 00:03:37,410
We'll start with the question.


62
00:03:37,410 --> 00:03:40,819
How come we keep digging the hole we are in?


63
00:03:40,819 --> 00:03:44,890
So why don’t we do what we know needs to
be done, you know, the things scientists have

64
00:03:44,890 --> 00:03:47,390
told us for ages we need to do?


65
00:03:47,390 --> 00:03:50,580
In our research, we learn something fascinating.


66
00:03:50,580 --> 00:03:56,480
It turns out that what we set our minds to,
what we think is possible or impossible,

67
00:03:56,480 --> 00:04:00,590
doesn't depend primarily on the
solutions we have or don't have.

68
00:04:00,590 --> 00:04:07,039
It depends on something deeper on the
stories, the deep stories that shape our thinking.

69
00:04:07,870 --> 00:04:12,379
Every group in history, every civilization
has a number of deep stories that shapes it.

70
00:04:12,379 --> 00:04:16,580
Collective stories that tell people
what to strive for, what a good

71
00:04:16,580 --> 00:04:19,009
life is and, and how the world works.


72
00:04:21,769 --> 00:04:26,630
Not so long ago, people in Europe and colonial
America took for granted that they were part

73
00:04:26,630 --> 00:04:29,960
of a feudal system with a king at the top.


74
00:04:29,960 --> 00:04:35,334
And when the King dies, however smart
or inept his first-born son happens to be,

75
00:04:35,334 --> 00:04:37,027
he gets to rule us all.


76
00:04:38,500 --> 00:04:41,419
People thought: this is how the
world works and will always work.

77
00:04:41,786 --> 00:04:45,452
Today, obviously, the idea seems quite ludicrous.


78
00:04:45,452 --> 00:04:51,041
Because at some point, and really,
quite quickly,in the late 18th century the story changed.

79
00:04:51,530 --> 00:04:56,005
Historians can argue endlessly about
“why” it suddenly changed, but the fact is:

80
00:04:56,005 --> 00:05:00,217
hundreds of thousands of people
stopped believing in the old story of feudalism.

81
00:05:00,217 --> 00:05:01,870
And embraced a new story.


82
00:05:03,247 --> 00:05:07,016
They wrote pamphlets, talked in
the streets,and fought for democracy.

83
00:05:07,130 --> 00:05:12,279
In just a few decades, the story of
self-rule became the dominant story.

84
00:05:13,289 --> 00:05:17,060
Of course, democracy at first
included only land-owning white men.

85
00:05:17,060 --> 00:05:22,000
It took a similar shift of stories to finally
end slavery and racial segregation in the

86
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:25,835
US, and that work is still very much ongoing.


87
00:05:26,560 --> 00:05:30,039
In the same vein, until just a
century ago, women weren't allowed to vote,

88
00:05:30,456 --> 00:05:32,041
and everyone took that for granted.


89
00:05:33,042 --> 00:05:36,520
A deep, collective story held
that women were inferior to men,

90
00:05:36,795 --> 00:05:39,006
and were not meant to have a public voice.


91
00:05:40,780 --> 00:05:43,889
A group of women rallied
to challenge that idea.

92
00:05:43,889 --> 00:05:48,015
It not only got women the right to vote, but
opened the doors to universities and the workplace.

93
00:05:48,015 --> 00:05:51,875
And all the other places
they used to be excluded from.


94
00:05:52,019 --> 00:05:55,022
This is how societies
make profound leaps forward.

95
00:05:55,770 --> 00:05:56,849
We often get this wrong.


96
00:05:56,849 --> 00:06:00,639
We focus on our presidents and
prime ministers and business leaders.

97
00:06:00,639 --> 00:06:03,270
They have the power to fix things, right?


98
00:06:03,270 --> 00:06:08,780
Well, they do, but just like all of us, what
they believe is possible is shaped by the

99
00:06:08,780 --> 00:06:11,734
deep stories that dominate our thinking.


100
00:06:11,918 --> 00:06:17,002
Update that story, and laws
and institutions often quickly follow.

101
00:06:17,190 --> 00:06:21,006
I want to highlight this fascinating fact.


102
00:06:21,871 --> 00:06:24,240
Profound change can happen quite quickly.


103
00:06:24,699 --> 00:06:29,014
But up until the moment it happens,
it often feels like nothing is moving,

104
00:06:29,014 --> 00:06:32,643
like nothing can beat the old story.


105
00:06:33,240 --> 00:06:36,021
But if you look under
the surface, that’s not true.

106
00:06:36,021 --> 00:06:38,370
Seeds are being planted.


107
00:06:38,370 --> 00:06:43,028
And more and more people are
leaving the old story for a better one.

108
00:06:44,289 --> 00:06:48,990
And then, when this reaches a critical mass,
like things suddenly shift much faster than

109
00:06:48,990 --> 00:06:50,035
anyone could have predicted.


110
00:06:50,035 --> 00:06:53,038
Sometimes in just a few years.


111
00:06:53,038 --> 00:06:55,666
And this is what gives me hope, you know,


112
00:06:55,666 --> 00:06:58,001
for the three crises we talked about last time.


113
00:06:59,002 --> 00:07:03,882
More and more of us all over the world
are working hard to bring about a better story.

114
00:07:04,440 --> 00:07:07,090
And right now things feel pretty stuck.


115
00:07:07,090 --> 00:07:11,014
But who knows how close
we could be to a tipping point


116
00:07:11,014 --> 00:07:13,750
where suddenly things change really fast.


117
00:07:13,750 --> 00:07:18,310
I don't know, but I like to try and feel
that like, can you imagine if we

118
00:07:18,310 --> 00:07:21,650
were at that stage where
suddenly things start to tip?


119
00:07:22,025 --> 00:07:28,000
Before we imagine a better future, let’s
take the time we need to really understand

120
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:30,659
the deep story that got us where we are.


121
00:07:31,034 --> 00:07:35,664
And it’s a story that tells us that:
“More is always better”.

122
00:07:36,039 --> 00:07:42,004
Like we always need to pursue more
because more will make us happy and safe.

123
00:07:42,629 --> 00:07:44,889
Some call it the “Story of More”.


124
00:07:46,008 --> 00:07:50,600
And at some point, we realized that this story
has seeped into every system that shapes our

125
00:07:50,600 --> 00:07:54,870
lives – that’s, you know, what deep stories do.


126
00:07:54,870 --> 00:07:56,289
Maybe you've noticed this too, right.


127
00:07:56,289 --> 00:08:02,024
The Story of More shapes how we produce food,
what we consume, how we produce energy,

128
00:08:02,024 --> 00:08:04,690
how we run our education systems, …


129
00:08:04,690 --> 00:08:09,060
In all of these places, we strive
for more, and more, and more.

130
00:08:09,060 --> 00:08:11,033
And at first, it makes sense…


131
00:08:11,450 --> 00:08:18,319
until we reach a point where instead of
bringing more happiness and more prosperity…


132
00:08:18,319 --> 00:08:22,002
it brings more loneliness and more destruction.


133
00:08:22,840 --> 00:08:27,820
Today we'll look at 3 of these systems - those
that are responsible for most of the destruction

134
00:08:27,820 --> 00:08:30,010
we talked about in episode 1.


135
00:08:30,010 --> 00:08:37,017
So, first we’ll look at Food, then
Consumption and Production, and finally Energy.

136
00:08:37,770 --> 00:08:42,022
And for each of them, we'll first
look at the old Story, the Story of More.

137
00:08:42,180 --> 00:08:46,026
So yeah, unfortunately, we'll
dwell a little bit more on the ugly stuff.

138
00:08:46,360 --> 00:08:51,448
But then, for all 3 topics, we'll also
look at a better story that is emerging.

139
00:08:52,032 --> 00:08:55,035
So, let’s start with our food system.


140
00:08:56,420 --> 00:08:57,420
Why food?


141
00:08:57,420 --> 00:09:02,560
What does it have to do with climate
change, or mass extinction or pollution?

142
00:09:02,560 --> 00:09:04,880
Well it turns out a lot, right!


143
00:09:04,880 --> 00:09:10,008
The way we produce food and transport it
and waste so much of it along the way,

144
00:09:10,008 --> 00:09:14,221
is a key driver of pollution and
the collapse of the living planet.

145
00:09:15,779 --> 00:09:19,434
And it produces 30% of all
the gas that warms our planet.

146
00:09:20,100 --> 00:09:23,029
Let’s just look at how eggs are produced.


147
00:09:23,029 --> 00:09:26,180
It used to be pretty straightforward.


148
00:09:26,180 --> 00:09:29,620
Every farmer used to have a few chickens in
their backyard that would eat bugs and food

149
00:09:29,620 --> 00:09:31,655
scraps and then lay eggs.


150
00:09:32,030 --> 00:09:34,658
Farmers knew their personalities.


151
00:09:35,410 --> 00:09:38,820
Just like humans, chickens form complex hierarchies.


152
00:09:38,820 --> 00:09:42,040
Some chickens are shy, some are
aggressive and some are curious.

153
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:45,002
But then, the Story of More took over.


154
00:09:45,540 --> 00:09:50,007
An accountant who owned some chickens
had the idea to put them in vertical cages,

155
00:09:50,300 --> 00:09:53,010
so you can concentrate
more chickens per square foot.


156
00:09:54,170 --> 00:10:00,017
That idea naturally led to cram more and
more chickens in each cage to maximize profit.

157
00:10:00,017 --> 00:10:03,770
Farmers were forced to play
along or they would be left behind.

158
00:10:03,770 --> 00:10:08,025
You could simply no longer
compete if you let your chickens run free.

159
00:10:08,850 --> 00:10:13,030
The trouble is: when chickens are confined
like this, in a way that nature never intended,

160
00:10:13,030 --> 00:10:15,810
they go mad and attack each other.


161
00:10:15,810 --> 00:10:21,100
An extra step was added to make this work
and keep the chickens from killing each other:

162
00:10:21,100 --> 00:10:26,001
the beaks of chicks are clipped or
burned off in a machine, with no anesthesia.

163
00:10:29,629 --> 00:10:34,290
Imagine how you would feel if you had to do
this job for 8 hours a day, burning off the

164
00:10:34,290 --> 00:10:36,550
beaks of thousands of chicks!


165
00:10:36,550 --> 00:10:39,920
Now, chickens can go mad
without killing each other.

166
00:10:39,920 --> 00:10:44,019
Which means you can stuff millions
of hens into gigantic egg factories.

167
00:10:45,130 --> 00:10:47,570
But that brings up another problem.


168
00:10:47,570 --> 00:10:51,026
When millions of animals are crammed
in a way that doesn’t happen in nature,

169
00:10:51,026 --> 00:10:55,520
infectious diseases evolve that
kill  off whole flocks, again and again.

170
00:10:55,520 --> 00:10:59,034
So all the chickens need to
be put on antibiotics, all the time.

171
00:11:00,035 --> 00:11:04,039
Without constant antibiotics,
the factory system would collapse.

172
00:11:05,829 --> 00:11:09,000
But far from being a solution,
this creates two new big problems.

173
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:11,004
Two ticking time bombs.


174
00:11:11,920 --> 00:11:16,843
For one, millions of animals sitting in their
own waste is the perfect breeding ground

175
00:11:16,843 --> 00:11:19,012
to grow deadly viruses.


176
00:11:20,013 --> 00:11:24,226
Experts warn us that if you want to
create a deadly, global pandemic for humans,

177
00:11:24,226 --> 00:11:26,645
just build factory farms.


178
00:11:27,760 --> 00:11:30,857
The second thing they worry about
is the massive overuse of antibiotics -

179
00:11:30,857 --> 00:11:33,470
the same antibiotics we humans use.


180
00:11:33,470 --> 00:11:37,870
It’ll breed bacteria that
become resistant to these antibiotics.


181
00:11:37,870 --> 00:11:39,250
And when that happens…


182
00:11:39,250 --> 00:11:44,037
well, surgery and childbirth will
gradually become a potentially fatal risk again,

183
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:45,980
as it used to be.


184
00:11:45,980 --> 00:11:48,667
Chemotherapy will no longer be safely practiced.


185
00:11:49,042 --> 00:11:53,790
Infectious diseases we have
forgotten will return to be deadly threats.


186
00:11:53,790 --> 00:11:56,007
That’s the Story of More.


187
00:11:57,720 --> 00:12:02,180
Every step has some logic to it, but it
ends up creating a Frankenstein system.

188
00:12:02,180 --> 00:12:09,170
Eggs are just one example, but the
story of factory farming is similar for turkeys,

189
00:12:09,170 --> 00:12:11,022
pigs, and cows.


190
00:12:12,330 --> 00:12:16,640
And to feed all these animals with soy
and grain, the pressure is relentless to take

191
00:12:16,640 --> 00:12:19,030
over more precious ecosystems.


192
00:12:19,830 --> 00:12:23,240
We get 18% of our energy
intake from meat and dairy.

193
00:12:23,240 --> 00:12:27,220
But it’s not 18% of the world’s
farmland that we use for meat and dairy.

194
00:12:27,220 --> 00:12:28,680
It’s… 83%.


195
00:12:29,040 --> 00:12:35,630
And that’s why we keep burning more
of the Amazon rainforest, bringing it closer to collapse.

196
00:12:37,215 --> 00:12:43,670
One thing we really, really ask you to do is:
don’t blame farmers for this absurd system!

197
00:12:43,670 --> 00:12:44,670
Yeah.


198
00:12:44,670 --> 00:12:48,490
Farmers feed us and the farmers
I know work harder than anyone else.

199
00:12:48,490 --> 00:12:51,399
Like they never get a day off, right?


200
00:12:51,399 --> 00:12:55,510
They're often the first one to suffer from
the system that they haven't chosen or even

201
00:12:55,510 --> 00:12:57,250
designed, right.


202
00:12:57,250 --> 00:13:01,639
In this system all of the profits get sucked
up out of the farms and farming communities

203
00:13:01,639 --> 00:13:04,420
into a few giant meat companies.


204
00:13:04,420 --> 00:13:09,910
And every year thousands of small farms,
you know, give up, crushed, you know by debts

205
00:13:09,910 --> 00:13:13,001
and by these giant factory farms.


206
00:13:13,001 --> 00:13:16,004
And it's a terrible deal
for us taxpayers too, right.

207
00:13:16,004 --> 00:13:21,000
Most of us don't realize, but we prop up
these gigantic factory farms

208
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:26,180
with millions of dollars, pounds and euros
of subsidies creating an uneven playing field

209
00:13:26,180 --> 00:13:30,040
that make it hard for smaller family farms.


210
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:36,024
The whole factory meat industry has become
so ugly that we’re not even allowed to see it.

211
00:13:36,830 --> 00:13:42,720
Did you know that in the US, meat lobbyists
convinced legislators in many states to make

212
00:13:42,720 --> 00:13:47,035
it a “terrorist” offense to
film inside factory farms?

213
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:51,665
No one is allowed to inform the
public about what’s going on inside!

214
00:13:53,170 --> 00:13:59,005
So over and over again, we’re led
to believe that the food we eat is this

215
00:13:59,005 --> 00:14:00,812
when really it’s this.


216
00:14:02,649 --> 00:14:05,850
And I hate that we have so little choice.


217
00:14:05,850 --> 00:14:09,750
Think about what you had to eat today,
you know... for breakfast or for lunch.

218
00:14:09,750 --> 00:14:12,750
I don't know, can you remember what it was?


219
00:14:12,750 --> 00:14:20,026
It's almost certain that if you had meat,
egg or dairy, it came from a factory farm, right.

220
00:14:20,026 --> 00:14:24,520
Even though it's entirely possible, as we'll
see, to raise animals in a different way that

221
00:14:24,520 --> 00:14:30,036
heals rather than destroys the planet,
but you're almost never given that option.

222
00:14:30,036 --> 00:14:32,060
And it’s not just meat.


223
00:14:32,060 --> 00:14:36,010
It’s the bread, the fruits
and vegetables we eat too.


224
00:14:36,010 --> 00:14:40,149
When chemical firms discovered they could
transform petroleum into cheap pesticides

225
00:14:43,870 --> 00:14:46,220
At first, it looked really promising.


226
00:14:46,220 --> 00:14:51,430
But now we wake up and see how vibrant ecosystems
have vanished at the hands of massive monocultures

227
00:14:51,430 --> 00:14:53,860
and pesticides.

