567
00:38:35,599 --> 00:38:39,560
help you repair stuff for free,
because they love doing it.

568
00:38:40,527 --> 00:38:46,040
It is way more fun than just buying
something new. You know, you're connected to

569
00:38:46,040 --> 00:38:50,460
this, you know, kid who goes to college
and you like, see that he can fix it and,

570
00:38:50,460 --> 00:38:53,039
you know, there's lots
of people who have different skills,

571
00:38:54,349 --> 00:38:59,290
Repair cafés, just like second hand shops,
toy and tool libraries help us get away from

572
00:38:59,290 --> 00:39:03,430
the old linear system of
“dig it, make it, trash it”.

573
00:39:03,430 --> 00:39:08,640
Instead, we move to a circular system
where we start with reducing what we produce and

574
00:39:08,640 --> 00:39:11,790
manufacture to only what is really needed.


575
00:39:11,790 --> 00:39:15,830
And then we share it, reuse it
and repair it over and over.

576
00:39:16,062 --> 00:39:19,770
And only when that’s no longer
possible, do we recycle it.

577
00:39:19,770 --> 00:39:25,030
And we do all of that without pollution and
without fossil fuels that overheat the planet.

578
00:39:27,032 --> 00:39:29,870
That’s the new story of consumption!


579
00:39:29,870 --> 00:39:33,246
But what about manufacturing and mass production?


580
00:39:33,455 --> 00:39:36,060
Is it possible to have
a better story there, too?

581
00:39:36,060 --> 00:39:38,930
I mean at a really large scale?


582
00:39:38,930 --> 00:39:46,009
Well, yes, Ray Anderson, a businessman
from Georgia is a great example of this.

583
00:39:46,850 --> 00:39:53,290
Ray founded a company called Interface in
1973 and grew it into the largest carpet manufacturer

584
00:39:53,290 --> 00:39:54,920
in the world.


585
00:39:54,920 --> 00:39:58,050
You know those 20-inch
carpet tiles you see in offices everywhere?

586
00:39:58,438 --> 00:40:00,023
That’s Interface.


587
00:40:00,648 --> 00:40:02,567
I was not an environmentalist.


588
00:40:02,567 --> 00:40:07,800
I hadn't given I had never given a thought
to what we were taking from the earth or doing

589
00:40:07,800 --> 00:40:10,920
to the earth to make our products.


590
00:40:10,920 --> 00:40:18,460
But when I found Hawkins book it was a
spear in the chest and I read it and wept because

591
00:40:18,666 --> 00:40:25,730
it just laid out so clearly the problems
of the industrial system, the system of which

592
00:40:25,730 --> 00:40:30,637
my company, my creation,
this third child of mine, was an integral part.

593
00:40:32,020 --> 00:40:34,680
At the time, Ray Anderson was 60.


594
00:40:34,680 --> 00:40:40,230
He realized that his business relied
on extracting 1.2 billion pounds of raw materials a year -

595
00:40:40,230 --> 00:40:46,653
most of it oil and natural gas that become
plastic fibers - to produce and ship millions of square

596
00:40:46,653 --> 00:40:52,659
yards of carpets to clients who,
a decade later, inevitably trash them in landfills.

597
00:40:53,829 --> 00:40:58,039
He set himself a goal, that in the
Story of More, would sound crazy:

598
00:40:58,248 --> 00:41:01,042
To bring the production process into a “closed loop” –


599
00:41:01,459 --> 00:41:06,101
no longer taking anything
from the earth but only recycle existing material.

600
00:41:06,101 --> 00:41:12,060
And to do that without polluting in any way.
It unleashed a whole wave of innovations.

601
00:41:12,060 --> 00:41:15,230
They redesigned their products and their machines.


602
00:41:15,230 --> 00:41:18,619
They began leasing their
carpets, instead of selling them.

603
00:41:18,619 --> 00:41:22,859
So that when the time comes to replace
the carpet, they can recuperate the tiles and

604
00:41:22,859 --> 00:41:24,700
recycle all of the materials.


605
00:41:24,700 --> 00:41:28,950
They switched the entire
production process to solar power.

606
00:41:28,950 --> 00:41:31,730
Sadly, Anderson died a few years ago.


607
00:41:31,730 --> 00:41:36,310
But today, his company is well and
on its way to meet his crazy goal: Shifting from

608
00:41:36,310 --> 00:41:42,041
a linear to a circular, closed-loop production,
something that at first was unimaginable.

609
00:41:42,876 --> 00:41:47,005
Interface is still the global
market leader, and they are highly profitable.

610
00:41:47,005 --> 00:41:52,010
And as you can imagine,
their workforce is incredibly proud to work there.

611
00:41:52,427 --> 00:41:58,740
Interface is now setting itself its
next big goal - not just to be carbon neutral, but

612
00:41:58,740 --> 00:42:00,480
to become “carbon negative”.


613
00:42:00,480 --> 00:42:05,780
You know, remember how with regenerative
farming, plants, you know, can draw down carbon from

614
00:42:05,780 --> 00:42:08,090
the atmosphere and store it in the ground?


615
00:42:08,090 --> 00:42:14,250
Well, with plant-based fibers, you know,
Interface is starting to store that carbon in the carpets.

616
00:42:14,866 --> 00:42:16,590
And Ray was ahead of his time.


617
00:42:16,590 --> 00:42:22,040
He happened to be in carpets,
but really any company can choose to do this.

618
00:42:22,040 --> 00:42:25,835
Imagine your workplace doing something similar.


619
00:42:25,835 --> 00:42:31,007
Like I don't know for you but
I would feel so motivated and so energized.

620
00:42:31,007 --> 00:42:34,010
And wow so proud!


621
00:42:34,219 --> 00:42:37,013
So that’s production and consumption.


622
00:42:37,222 --> 00:42:41,017
And to round this out let’s talk about
